<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>
Native American Legends: Lone Man (Only Man)
</H1>



<font size=4>
<b>Name:</B> Lone Man<BR>
<b>Tribal affiliation:</B> <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/mandan_culture.htm">Mandan</a>, 
<a href="http://www.bigorrin.org/hidatsa_kids.htm">Hidatsa</a><BR>
<b>Also known as:</B> Only Man, One Man<BR>
<b>Native names:</B> Macéruwacash, Numank Maxana, Numakmaxena, Numak-Mahana<BR>
<b>Type:</B> <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/culture-heroes.htm">Culture hero</a><BR>
<b>Related figures in other tribes:</B> <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/little-hare.htm">Little Hare</a> (Omaha), 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/nanabozho.htm">Nanabush</A> (Ojibway), 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/glooskap.htm">Glooscap</A> (Wabanaki)
<BR>
<BR>
</font>

Lone Man is the mythical first human and culture hero of the Mandan and Hidatsa tribes. 
He worked together with Coyote to shape the earth and teach the people how to live. 

